111	<body>
112	
113	<div class="title-row">
114	  <h1>Greenroom Case Study Memo</h1>
115	  <div class="byline">Chip Herndon · May 20, 2026</div>
116	</div>
117	
118	<p>The settlment product currently lacks direction and tells no clear settlement story. Resulting in downstream confusion and the observed lack of adoption. This memo defines and defends the slice required to create that direction.</p>
119	
120	<h2>The slice</h2>
121	<p>Give Mariana a settlement she can trust: the deal terms she negotiates over email captured at deal creation in structured fields, and the math she walks the agent through at 2am rendered as a line-by-line statement the tour manager can trace. These two moments, deal modeling and the 2am walkthrough, are the bookends of every settlement; their mishandling is the clearest evidence of the product's missing direction. The slice aims to provide the improvements for those bookends to function as required.</p>
122	
123	<h2>Why this cut</h2>
124	<p>Deep exploration of the product and provided materials surfaced several obvious problem areas:</p>
125	
126	<ul>
127	  <li><strong>Deal modeling</strong> — only flat and %-of-gross settle in-app, vs and %-of-net (the majority of bookings) are unsupported.</li>
128	  <li><strong>Recoup terms</strong> — no structured representation, lives entirely in prose.</li>
129	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> — distributed across accounts, manual entry, dominates Mariana's time.</li>
130	  <li><strong>Deal renegotiation</strong> — terms change after initial entry; structured fields don't allow for updates.</li>
131	  <li><strong>Recoup lifecycle</strong> — recoups have their own state (agreed/disputed/withdrawn) independent of the settlement's.</li>
132	  <li><strong>Dispute resolution</strong> — no way to handle disputed settlements in our product.</li>
133	  <li><strong>Real-time prediction</strong> — predict whether a settlement will be clean vs messy before show day.</li>
134	  <li><strong>Post-show comms</strong> — no clean way to share traceable settlement math after the show.</li>
135	  <li><strong>Lifecycle hygiene</strong> — UI status and underlying data disagree (the brief's spotting-it test).</li>
136	  <li><strong>Cap enforcement</strong> — expense and hospitality caps are set at deal time but no part of the workflow enforces them.</li>
137	</ul>
138	
139	<p>Each problem was ruled against the same question: <em>does fixing it significantly address why 82% of customers don't use the in-app tool?</em> Most fail. <strong>Expense management</strong> is the loudest transcript pain point, but the collection problem (distributed accounts) is upstream of Greenroom and spreadsheets have the same problem, a fix here doesn't move adoption. <strong>Renegotiation, recoup lifecycle, and cap enforcement</strong> are live issues and belong on the roadmap, but they're edit-time workflow and runtime enforcement gaps that build on top of structured deal entry (not implemented). <strong>Disputes, post-show comms, and lifecycle hygiene</strong> are downstream effects of unclear deal creation, which the dispute thread proved with unclear terms on how the recoup would be calculated. <strong>Real-time prediction</strong> is a new feature unrelated to core issues, therefore out of scope.</p>
140	
141	<p>Three findings from querying the database directly anchor this cut:</p>
142	<ol>
143	  <li><strong>Percentage drift</strong> — a deal's <code>dealNotesFreetext</code> describes an 85/15 net split after renegotiation, but <code>deals.percentage</code> still reads <code>0.75</code>. The engine reads the structured field, so the artist would be paid 10% less than negotiated.</li>
144	  <li><strong>Incorrect dispute state</strong> — <code>settlements.status = "disputed"</code> while <code>settlements.signoffText</code> reads "Looks good — TM. Wire to the usual account." The internal <code>notes</code> field clarifies the TM signed off Sunday; his assistant flagged a production-overage line Monday. Three fields, three versions of truth in one record.</li>
145	  <li><strong>Systemic recoup disputes</strong> — querying <code>settlements.recoupsJson</code> for <code>status = "disputed"</code> and joining to artist→agent surfaces five Daniel Hwang (WME) shows with disputed <code>marketing</code> recoups. Issue is recurring.</li>
146	</ol>
147	
148	<p>Capturing deal terms structurally at creation and upgrading the engine to industry standards will move adoption and lower dispute rates, while resolving the downstream issues. Feature requests move onto the roadmap where they belong.</p>
149	
150	<h2>Design choices</h2>
151	
152	<h3>Data model</h3>
153	<p><strong>JSON columns over new tables.</strong> Recoup clauses live as <code>recoupClausesJson</code> on the deal; settlement-time applications stay in the existing <code>recoupsJson</code>. New tables would have been cleaner, but with 340 production venues, migration coordination would have dwarfed the slice. The codebase already used JSON for bonuses, so the pattern is native. Trade-off: cross-deal querying is weaker.</p>
154	
155	<p><strong>Clause vs application split.</strong> Negotiated rights (deal-time) and billed amounts (settlement-time) are deliberately separate, joined by clause ID. Collapsing them loses the "negotiated X / billed Y / disputed Z" view — the exact distinction the Coastal Spell dispute hinged on. Trade-off: two JSON shapes to keep in sync, mitigated by typed parsers.</p>
156	
157	<h3>Engine contract</h3>
158	<p><strong>Hard-fail with a typed error contract.</strong> Unsupported and misconfigured deals return <code>kind: "deal_type_unsupported" | "deal_misconfigured"</code>; the UI renders a deliberately jarring empty state. This avoids silent fallback to $0 or partial math that would produce disputes. Visible failure is honest and maintains trust.</p>
159	
160	<p><strong>Door deals explicitly out of scope.</strong> The schema declares <code>dealType: "door"</code> but ticketing doesn't split door receipts from presales, so the basis can't be computed. Rather than guess, door deals hard-fail with a clear reason.</p>
161	
162	<p><strong>Capacity-fraction ratchets inferred from data, not schema.</strong> The existing data has two coexisting ratchet shapes (dollar-axis bands and capacity-fraction step functions) under one schema. The engine infers basis from tier values (<code>&lt; 1</code> ⇒ capacity, otherwise dollars) and branches accordingly. A schema-level <code>basis</code> discriminator is the right end state and is marked TODO; doing it now would force a backfill on the case-study snapshot.</p>
163	
164	<h3>UI ↔ engine fidelity</h3>
165	<p><strong>Worksheet renders directly from engine output.</strong> Every row on the page is a <code>SettlementStep</code> the engine emitted; the UI does no derived math. Sarah's "itemization + provenance" requirement breaks without this rule. Trade-off: the engine emits display-shaped steps (a <code>kind</code> field per row), slightly conflating math and presentation; mitigated by typing.</p>
166	
167	<p><strong>PDF export of the worksheet.</strong> Once the engine's step list became canonical, exporting it as a PDF was a small addition — wire the existing steps through <code>jsPDF</code>. The artifact gives Mariana something traceable to send the tour manager, addressing most of the post-show comms problem without making it its own slice.</p>
168	
169	<p><strong>Math-first test suite.</strong> 29 vitest tests covering every deal-type path, both ratchet bases, all recoup waterfall positions, overage owners, parser hardening, and the Coastal Spell regression. The existential risk is silent math drift; the tier-ratchet bug hid in plain sight for months before this work caught it.</p>
170	
171	<h3>User trust &amp; migration</h3>
172	<p><strong>Kept <code>dealNotesFreetext</code>.</strong> Prose is what Mariana trusts today; structured fields should earn trust over time. Forcing migration loses the user or, at minimum, provokes anxiety. The slice makes structured <em>valuable enough</em> that prose becomes redundant — it doesn't ban prose by decree. Trade-off: prose and structure can still drift; surfacing both side-by-side on the show page makes drift visible.</p>
173	
174	<h2>How I'll validate</h2>
175	<p>The leading metric is in-app adoption. If 18% becomes 35% in two quarters at venues with this slice rolled out, the slice worked. If it doesn't move, the slice didn't address the actual blocker — and we need to find out fast whether that's because the structured fields still don't fit real deals, because Mariana doesn't trust the math enough to abandon her spreadsheet, or because the rendering doesn't beat her sheet's clarity. Adoption is the right north star because it's the only metric downstream of every assumption the slice makes. Secondary metrics: decreases in dispute rate on in-app-settled shows, and decreases in the use of the <code>dealNotesFreetext</code> field.</p>
176	
177	<h2>What needs to be shipped next</h2>
178	<ol>
179	  <li><strong>Renegotiation workflow</strong> — structured fields go stale when terms change post-inception. Build a "renegotiate" action that requires structured re-entry.</li>
180	  <li><strong>Recoup lifecycle as a first-class state machine</strong> — gives orphaned recoups a queue users can work through separate from the parent settlement.</li>
181	  <li><strong>Two-sided agent view of structured deal terms</strong> — gives the agent a full lifecycle view of upcoming settlements, fostering trust between our customer and the agent.</li>
182	  <li><strong>Door deal support</strong> — for completeness of the <code>dealMath.ts</code> engine, once ticketing splits door receipts from presales.</li>
183	  <li><strong>Pre-show deal health prediction</strong> — Marcus's explicit ask, now possible because of the structured data model. Nice-to-have for decision-making customers.</li>
184	  <li><strong>Expense management</strong> — highest-impact item on the broader roadmap. Major refactor of collection and reporting, likely including OCR/AI workflow. Huge time unlock for customers, but a major undertaking; should not be considered until the rest of the settlement product has met the craft bar.</li>
185	</ol>
186	
187	</body>
188	</html>
